{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8be514b7-947e-412e-b676-9b79c08bef7c","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2 / .NET 9**, so you have the full modern feature set. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n- **Constructor** → inject `TestContext` + synchronous setup\n- **`[TestInitialize]` async** → asynchronous setup\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private HttpClient _client = null!;\n\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        // TestContext injected via constructor (MSTest v3+)\n        _testContext = testContext;\n\n        // Synchronous init here\n    }\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task InitAsync()\n    {\n        // Async init here\n        _client = new HttpClient();\n        await _client.GetAsync(\"https://example.com/health\");\n    }\n\n    [TestCleanup]\n    public async Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        _client.Dispose();\n        await Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test...\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_client);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points for MSTest 3.x:**\n\n| Concern | Mechanism |\n|---|---|\n| `TestContext` | Constructor injection (no property needed) |\n| Sync init | Constructor body |\n| Async init | `[TestInitialize] async Task` |\n| Class-level async | `[ClassInitialize] static async Task` |\n\nThe older `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property approach still works but constructor injection is preferred in v3+.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9fa4ca6f-e62f-4c3b-924c-4aaa328e1ca5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In modern MSTest (v3+), the recommended approach is:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: Use a constructor parameter or a `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property. In MSTest v3+, constructor injection is supported.\n\n2. **Synchronous initialization**: Implement `[TestInitialize]` method.\n\n3. **Asynchronous initialization**: In MSTest v3, `[TestInitialize]` can be async (return `Task`). Alternatively, you can implement `IAsyncInitialization` or just use `async Task` with `[TestInitialize]`.\n\n\nIn MSTest v3, TestContext can be injected directly through the constructor, and both `[TestInitialize]` and `[ClassInitialize]` support async Task return types. The modern pattern involves injecting TestContext via constructor and using async initialization methods as needed.\n\nHowever, I'm realizing you can only have one `[TestInitialize]` method per class. If you need both synchronous and asynchronous setup, the best approach is to use a single async `[TestInitialize]` method that handles both types of work—calling synchronous setup code directly and awaiting any async operations. Alternatively, you could handle synchronous initialization in the constructor and reserve `[TestInitialize]` for async work.\n\nFor injecting `TestContext` in MSTest v3, constructor injection is now supported with C# 12+, which is cleaner than the traditional property approach. Given you're on .NET 9 and MSTest 3.8.2, the recommended pattern is to inject `TestContext` through the constructor, do synchronous initialization there, and then use an async `[TestInitialize]` method for any asynchronous setup work.","outputTokens":1111,"requestId":"4C4E:1005AF:C41F67:F24597:6A0131E4"},"id":"7c31dc16-be5c-4b41-8651-8500a6c64a52","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:33:45.593Z","parentId":"04e3f867-5b3f-4217-8ce0-caa091add8c2"}
